1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 5. f4 c5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Be3 a6 8. a3 {
This is a rare move. Usually White plays 8.Qd2 b5 and here 9.a3. To my mind,
Topalov's choice won't find many followers. After the move in text Black might
save a tempo by refraining from ...b7-b5, at least for a while. It is
interesting that on the next day Topalov employed the same line as Black,
against his second Ivan Cheparinov.} ({Cheparinov didn't follow the main line
either:} 8. Ne2 Be7 9. c3 O-O 10. g3 cxd4 11. Nexd4 Nc5 12. Bg2 Bd7 13. O-O Rc8
$11 {0-1 Cheparinov,I (2696)-Topalov,V (2767)/Sofia BUL 2008/The Week in Chess
705 (38)}) 8... cxd4 9. Nxd4 Bc5 10. Be2 {Topalov is trying to steal a tempo,
in case that Black will go for a standard overall exchange on d4 followed by
Qd8-b6.} (10. Qd2 Bxd4 11. Bxd4 Nxd4 12. Qxd4 Qb6 13. Qxb6 Nxb6 {In this
endgame White has a slight edge but, usually Black keeps the balance without
many difficulties.} 14. Bd3 Bd7 15. Ne2 f6 16. Kd2 fxe5 17. fxe5 Ke7 18. Rhf1
Raf8 {+/=/= 1/2-1/2 Psakhis,L (2560)-Drasko,M (2510)/Moscow 1988/CBM 009 (28)})
(10. g3 Qb6 11. Na4 Qa5+ 12. Nc3 Qb6 13. Na4 Qa5+ 14. Nc3 Qc7 15. Nce2 O-O 16.
Bg2 Nxd4 17. Nxd4 Nb6 18. b3 f6 $1 19. exf6 e5 $1 20. fxe5 Qxe5 21. Qd2 Rxf6
$36 {0-1 Lalic,B (2548)-Kortschnoj,V (2659)/Calcutta 2000/CBM 074 ext (47)})
10... O-O {Of course, Black is not forced to go for the exchange on d4 so
quickly.} 11. Qd2 Qc7 ({Now the exchange} 11... Nxd4 12. Bxd4 Bxd4 13. Qxd4 Qb6
{is a bit worse for Black, since in the forthcoming endgame the king is on an
inferior g8 location, compared to an ideal e7 square.}) 12. Bf3 $6 {Topalov
vacates the e2 square for the knight but, loses control over the f1-a6
diagonal which will be exploited by Ivanchuk a few moves later. It would have
been more natural and preferable to complete his development.} (12. O-O b5 (
12... Nxd4 13. Bxd4 Qb6 14. Rfd1 {+/=/=} Qxb2 $4 15. Rdb1 $18 {[%csl Rb2]}) 13.
Rad1 {White's position is very solid in this case.} ({Worthy of consideration
was} 13. Rf3 $5 Bb7 14. Rg3 {trying to harass the black monarch.})) 12... Nxd4
13. Bxd4 Nb6 14. Ne2 Bxd4 (14... Nc4 $6 {is a punch in the air.} 15. Qc3 {
[%cal Gb2b3]}) 15. Qxd4 Bd7 16. b3 {If it were White's turn, after QQd4-d2
followed by Ne2-d4 White's position would be very good. However, Black is just
in time to prevent this regrouping.} ({The immediate} 16. Qd2 $6 Rac8 17. Nd4
$2 {would fall into} Nc4 18. Qc3 Nxe5 $1 19. Qxc7 Nxf3+ 20. Nxf3 Rxc7 {and
Black is a healthy pawn up.}) 16... Bb5 $1 (16... f6 $6 {is too risky.} 17.
exf6 gxf6 18. O-O e5 19. fxe5 fxe5 20. Qd2 $14 {Black's monarch is vulnerable
and his pawn centre is not so tough.} (20. Bxd5+ $4 Kg7 21. Qd2 Qc5+ $19)) 17.
Nc3 $2 {After this move Black seizes the intiative.} ({By} 17. Qc3 Qxc3+ 18.
Nxc3 Rfc8 19. Kd2 Rc5 20. Nxb5 axb5 21. c3 Rac8 22. Rhc1 $11 {Topalov could
get a much better version of the endgame that arose later in the game.}) 17...
Rfc8 18. Nxb5 axb5 19. Be2 Nd7 20. Ra2 {If White has to make such an awkward
move, this means that something went definitely wrong.} (20. Bd3 Nc5 $17) 20...
Nb8 $1 {Transfering the knight to better pastures.} 21. O-O Nc6 22. Qd2 Qb6+ {
Before proposing the exchange of queens, it is useful to drive away the white
king far from the centre.} 23. Kh1 Qa5 {White is nearly forced to exchange
queens under unfavourable circumstances.} 24. Qxa5 Rxa5 25. Raa1 Rca8 ({
Probably stronger would have been} 25... Nd4 26. Bd3 Rca8 $17 {The knight on
d4 also prevents the counterplay f4-f5 that occurred later in the game.}) 26.
Rad1 Rxa3 27. Bxb5 Nb4 28. c4 {Practically forced.} R8a5 $2 {Wasting time and
weakening the back rank. It should be noted that Ivanchuk was in a severe
time-scramble.} (28... Rxb3 29. cxd5 Nxd5 30. Bc4 Rb4 31. Bxd5 exd5 32. Rxd5
Rxf4 $1 33. Kg1 {White should hold this endgame.}) (28... g6 $5 $15) 29. f5
exf5 30. g4 $1 {Well played. This move was definitely unpleasant for Ivanchuk,
especially in time-trouble.} Rxb3 (30... fxg4 31. Bd7 $1 {[%cal Ge5e6]} dxc4
32. e6 Re5 33. exf7+ Kf8 34. Bxg4 Ra8 35. bxc4 {and White survives.}) 31. gxf5
Re3 $2 (31... Rb2 32. e6 Raa2 33. Rfe1 Rxh2+ 34. Kg1 Rag2+ 35. Kf1 {and Black
has no more than a perpetual check.}) 32. Rb1 Nd3 33. e6 $2 {Missing the
chance.} (33. Ra1 $1 Rxa1 34. Rxa1 g5 35. cxd5 Nxe5 36. d6 {and Black can't
stop the d-pawn and has to give up a knight.}) 33... d4 {According to the
evidence, Ivanchuk had about only 7 seconds for 7 remaining moves until the
move 40 (no increment!). So, at this point his prior task was to be able not
to lose on time...} 34. Be8 $2 (34. Bc6 $1 Nc5 35. Bxb7 fxe6 36. fxe6 Nxb7 37.
Rxb7 h6 38. e7 Rae5 $11) 34... Nc5 {Finally, the knight has arrived at a
perfect outpost.} 35. Bxf7+ Kf8 36. f6 gxf6 37. Rxf6 Ke7 {Now Black has
perfect harmony between all his pieces.} 38. Rh6 d3 39. Rxh7 d2 40. Rg1 Re1 41.
Bh5+ Kxe6 {With some ups and downs, Ivanchuk gloriously survived the
incredible time-scramble. Topalov can resign now, the d-pawn decides the
outcome.} 42. Rhg7 Ne4 43. R7g6+ Ke5 {A dramatic finish of a very important
encounter!} 0-1

