1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 5. f4 c5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Be3 a6 {It is
curious that Topalov follows the opening line which he played in previous
round ... as White against Vassily Ivanchuk.} 8. Ne2 {Not a common move. I
guess that Chepatrinov wanted to deviate both from the main line 8.Qd2 and
from the game Topalov-Ivanchuk played in the 2nd round.} (8. a3 cxd4 9. Nxd4
Bc5 10. Be2 O-O 11. Qd2 Qc7 12. Bf3 Nxd4 13. Bxd4 Nb6 14. Ne2 Bxd4 15. Qxd4 Bd7
$11 {0-1 Topalov,V (2767)-Ivanchuk,V (2740)/Sofia BUL 2008/The Week in Chess
705 (43)}) ({The main theoretical line is} 8. Qd2 b5 9. a3 {and here Black can
try out Morozevich's idea} g5 $5) 8... Be7 {This move hadn't appeared on the
top level beforehand. Probably Topalov was trying to deviate from the main
lines which were definitely analysed by Cheparinov, especially after the game
Topalov-Morozevich which was played in Morelia/Linares 2007.} (8... Qb6 9. Qc1
g5 $5 (9... f6 $5 {is a serious alternative suggested by Mihail Marin.} 10. c3
Be7 11. g3 O-O $132) 10. c3 cxd4 11. cxd4 Bb4+ 12. Kf2 f6 13. g3 Rf8 14. Kg2 g4
15. Nh4 $14 {1-0 Topalov,V (2783)-Morozevich,A (2741)/Morelia/Linares 2007/CBM
117 (48)}) 9. c3 O-O 10. g3 cxd4 11. Nexd4 (11. cxd4 Nb6 12. b3 Bd7 {and Black
will slowly, but surely develop his play on the queenside. Meanwhile, White's
attacking chances on the kingside are murky.}) 11... Nc5 {The knight is
heading to e4. It can be concluded that Black has solved his opening problems,
the position is equal.} 12. Bg2 Bd7 (12... f6 $6 {would play into White's
hands.} 13. exf6 Rxf6 14. O-O $16 {and after the exchange on c6 followed by
Be3-d4 White will be in possession of an initiative.}) 13. O-O Rc8 14. Kh1 Ne4
({It was possible to go for knight moves on the queenside straight away:} 14...
Na5 {[%cal Ga5c4]} 15. Nd2 Na4 16. Rb1 (16. Qc2 $2 Ba3 $1 17. bxa3 Rxc3 $19 {
[%csl Rc2,Re3]}) 16... Nb6 17. f5 Nac4 18. Nxc4 Nxc4 19. Bf4 exf5 20. Bxd5 Rc5
21. Bxb7 Qc7 22. Bxa6 Nxe5 $44) 15. Nxc6 $1 {Eliminating the knight before it
comes via a5 to c4.} bxc6 16. c4 a5 $6 {I don't like this move, since it takes
an important square from black's queen.} (16... Qa5 17. Qc2 Rb8 {looks more to
the point.}) 17. Qc2 g6 18. Rad1 Nc5 19. Nd4 {Black's only active piece is
driven away from it's outpost. White is clearly better. His plan is an assault
against the black monarch.} Qc7 {Eyeing the Pe5. However, it does not really
prevent from White his natural attacking plan by f4-f5.} 20. g4 Rfd8 $6 {
Topalov does not sense the danger. Moving away the rook from the f-file makes
Black's king more vulnerable.} (20... f6 21. exf6 Bxf6 22. cxd5 cxd5 23. f5
gxf5 24. gxf5 Kh8 25. fxe6 Nxe6 26. Qd2 Bg7 27. Bxd5 Qe5 {Black is a pawn down
but, after the forthcoming massive simplifications his chances for a draw are
reasonable. This is because very few pawns are left on the board.}) 21. Qf2 Be8
(21... dxc4 22. f5 exf5 23. gxf5 Qxe5 24. fxg6 fxg6 25. Qf7+ Kh8 26. Ne6 Nxe6
27. Qxe7 Qxe3 28. Rf7 Kg8 29. Rg7+ Nxg7 30. Qxe3 $16) 22. f5 $1 {Everything is
ready for an assault.} Qxe5 ({White gets a strong attack also after} 22... exf5
23. Nxf5 $1 gxf5 24. gxf5 {[%csl Rc5,Rg8][%cal Gf2g3,Gf5f6]}) 23. fxe6 $2 {It
is logical to open the f-file.  However, It would have been far stronger to
start with the tempting move 23.Nf3 followed by 24.fxg6, not allowing Black's
knight to join the defence.} (23. Nf3 $1 Qd6 24. fxg6 {All the variations show
that Black does not have a satisfactory defence.} fxg6 (24... hxg6 25. Ng5 f6 (
25... Bxg5 26. Bxg5 $40) 26. Bxc5 Qxc5 27. Qxc5 Bxc5 28. Nxe6 $18) 25. Ng5 Nd7
(25... Bxg5 26. Bxc5 Bh4 27. Qg1 Qc7 28. Qe3 Bf7 29. Qh6 g5 30. Qf6 $18 {[%cal
Gc5d4,Gc5e7]}) (25... e5 26. Qh4 Bxg5 27. Bxg5 Rd7 28. Rf6 Ne6 29. c5 $1 $18)
26. Nf7 Bxf7 27. Qxf7+ Kh8 28. Bf4 e5 29. Bh6 Rg8 30. cxd5 c5 31. Qe6 $18 {
[%cal Gf1f7]}) 23... Nxe6 24. Nxe6 (24. Rde1 $6 Bd6 25. Nf3 Qg7 {defending
successfully.}) 24... Qxe6 25. Rde1 $1 {White should not care about such a
small detail as Pg4.} Qxg4 26. Bd4 $2 {This is a typical situation when a
player, being on the offensive, misses a point where it's already necessary to
guarantee himself equality.} (26. Bc5 Bxc5 27. Rxe8+ Rxe8 28. Qxf7+ Kh8 29.
Qf6+ {with a perpetual check was the objective result at this point.}) 26...
Qh4 27. Rxe7 Qxe7 28. Re1 (28. Bf6 Qf8 {White does not have anything better
than to win back the exchange which will leave him simply two pawns down.})
28... Qg5 29. Re5 (29. h4 Qf5 30. Qxf5 gxf5 31. Rg1 Rd6 32. h5 Kf8 33. Bc5 Ke7
34. Re1+ Kd7 35. Bh3 {would have been objectively better but, who wants to go
to a worse endgame in such a position?!}) 29... Qc1+ 30. Re1 Qg5 31. Re5 f5 {
Of course, no repetition. White's attack evaporates, while Black's extra
material decides the outcome.} 32. h4 Qg4 33. Kh2 (33. Bf3 Qh3+ 34. Kg1 Bf7 $19
) 33... dxc4 34. Bh3 Qd1 35. Re1 Rxd4 $1 (35... Qxd4 $4 36. Rxe8+ $1) 36. Rxd1
Rxd1 {Black has too much material for the queen.} 37. Bf1 Bf7 38. Be2 {White
resigned.} 0-1

