1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 O-O 8. a4
b4 9. d3 d6 10. Nbd2 Na5 11. Ba2 c5 12. c3 Rb8 ({This is more popular and
possibly bettar than} 12... Nc6 {Anand,V (2792)-Grischuk,A (2726)/Mexico City
2007/CBM 120/[Marin,M] (1-0, 50)}) 13. d4 Qc7 14. dxe5 {White releases the
tension in the centre in order to ensure the c4-square for his knight.} (14.
Nf1 {was examined in the comments to the aforementioned game.}) 14... dxe5 15.
Nc4 Rd8 {The obvious drawback of the early exchange of pawns, but there is no
such thing as the perfect move in the well-analyzed opening variations...} 16.
Qe2 b3 $5 {The operation initiated by this move is likely to lead to the loss
of a pawn, but, hopefully, White's normal development will be slowed down.
From strategic point of view, Black is more or less forced to play so, in
order to prevent White from obtaining a perfect blockade on light squares.} 17.
Nxa5 {Forced.} (17. Bb1 $4 {would be an irremediable blunder, because after}
Nxc4 18. Qxc4 Be6 {followed by ...c4, White's would play the rest of the game
without his light-squared bishop and queen's rook. He cannot even get some
counterplay with} 19. Qxa6 {because after} c4 {the queen would share a similar
fate, being under the additional threat of being captured.}) 17... Qxa5 18. Bb1
c4 $5 $146 {The most consistent continuation. Black immediately gives up the
c-pawn, in order to keep the enemy bishop (and the a1-rook) passive for as
long as possible. At the same time, the c5-square is cleared for the black
pieces.} ({Half-measures would not work out well. After} 18... Qc7 $6 19. Bd3
$1 $14 {White achieved his main strategic aim.} a5 20. Bg5 {[%csl Rd5][%cal
Gg5f6,Gd3c4,Gf3d2]} Nh5 21. Be3 $1 {The exchange of the light-squared bishops
would relieve Black's position.} Bb7 22. Bc4 h6 (22... Bxe4 23. Ng5 Bg6 24.
Nxf7 Bxf7 25. Bxf7+ Kxf7 26. Qxh5+ Kg8 27. Rad1 $14 {leaves Black with lots of
weaknesses. However, White should be careful not to allow the far advanced
enemy pawns become mobile by tactical means (for instance, with ...Ba3, in
case of mass simplifications).}) 23. Nd2 Nf4 24. Bxf4 exf4 25. Nxb3 $16 {
Carlsen,M (2714)-Adams,M (2729)/Moscow 2007/EXT 2008 (1-0, 63)}) 19. Qxc4 ({
The main alternative is to capture with the knight:} 19. Nd2 Bg4 $5 20. Nxc4 (
20. f3 $2 Qc5+ 21. Kh1 Be6 $19 {[%csl Ra1,Rb1]}) 20... Qc5 21. Qf1 Be6 22. Ne3
{True, White's position temporarily looks passive, but Black has to work out
some tactical details in order to prevent the favourable occupation of the
d5-square by means of c4 and Nd5.[%csl Rd5][%cal Gc3c4,Gb1d3]}) 19... Bc5 {
This tempting move will eventually lead to simplifications. Since the highest
priority is to prevent the re-development of the b1-bishop, it would have made
sense to double rooks along the d-file as soon as possible. However, choosing
the optimal form to do it is far from easy.} ({For instance,} 19... Rb7 {may
not be that good, because it would create some problems of coordination after
[%cal Gb7d7]} 20. Qe2 Rbd7 21. h3 {[%cal Gc1e3]} (21. Be3 Ng4 $15) {For
instance} 21... Qc7 (21... Bb7 22. Qc4 {[%cal Gc4b3]}) 22. Be3 Bb7 23. a5 {
[%cal Ge3b6]} Bc5 24. Bxc5 Qxc5 25. Ra3 {[%cal Ga3b3]}) 20. h3 {With his
development incomplete yet, White has to be careful.} (20. Qe2 $6 Ng4 21. Rf1
Qb6 22. Bd2 (22. h3 Nxf2 $1) 22... a5 23. h3 Ba6 24. c4 Nxf2 25. Rxf2 Bxc4 26.
Qxc4 Bxf2+ 27. Kh1 Be3 $17) 20... Qb6 21. Be3 (21. Qe2 Qd6) 21... Bxe3 22. Rxe3
Rd1+ 23. Re1 Rxe1+ 24. Nxe1 {White's placement of his pieces does not look
that great, but he has maintained his extra pawn and enabled the
re-development of the bishop.} Be6 25. Qe2 Nd7 26. a5 Qd6 27. Bd3 Nc5 28. Bc4
Bxc4 29. Qxc4 g6 30. Nf3 Rd8 {Still, Black has stabilized the queenside
position, where he is a pawn down, maintaining firm control of the only open
file.} 31. Re1 Qc7 32. g3 Kg7 33. Re2 Rd3 34. Kg2 Qd6 35. Ng5 {The only wing
where White can hope to make some progress is the kingside.} (35. h4 {comes
into consideration, too.[%cal Gh4h5]}) 35... Qe7 36. Re3 $6 {White
unnecessarily spoils his pawn structure and weakens the king's position.} (36.
Nxf7 Qxf7 37. Qxc5 {is met by} Qf3+ {when White has to find the only saving
move} 38. Kh2 Qxe2 39. Qe7+ {with perpetual.} Kh6 40. Qf8+ Kh5 41. g4+ Kg5 $8
$11) ({He was under no immediate threat and could have started a slow
positional attack onthe kingside with} 36. h4 {for instance} Kg8 {What else?
Black is in some sort of zugzwang, with his pieces placed on optimal position
already.} (36... Rd1 $6 37. Re3 $1 {[%cal Ge3f3]} h6 38. Nxf7 Nd7 39. Qxb3 Rd2
